          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829241?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">今年 5 月，土耳其支持的一名宪兵在叙利亚西北部据报道被阿布·侯赛因·古莱希 (Abu al-Husayn al-Qurayshi) 使用的房屋外站岗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Bakr Alkasem/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108092"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 2:57 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伊斯坦布尔——伊斯兰国周四证实，其鲜为人知的最高领导人已被杀，这是该极端组织的高级领导人在不到两年的时间里第三次遭遇这种命运。</p><p>该组织在其发言人的一份音频声明中表示，其前任领导人代号阿布·侯赛因·古莱希 (Abu al-Husayn al-Qurayshi) 在与控制叙利亚西北部部分地区的敌对武装组织沙姆解放组织 (Hayat Tahrir al-Sham) 的冲突中身亡。 。</p><p>几个月前，土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-leader-killed-in-intelligence-operation-turkeys-erdogan-says-93f844cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，伊斯兰国领导人在土耳其在叙利亚北部的一次情报行动中被打死</a>。</p><p>该组织任命了新领导人阿布·哈夫斯·哈希米·古莱希 (Abu Hafs al-Hashimi al-Qurayshi)。据极端主义专家称，该组织的最新任最高指挥官在负责该组织期间没有发表公开声明。</p><p> 2014年，“伊斯兰国”控制了伊拉克和叙利亚大片地区，对数百万人实施残酷的宗教统治，并在全球范围内发起针对平民的暴力袭击行动。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>经过伊拉克和叙利亚军队在美国空军支持下多年的压倒性军事行动后，该组织于 2019 年失去了对叙利亚最后一块领土的控制。</p><p>该组织一直是一个地下激进组织，仍然有能力实施致命暴力。 2022 年初，其武装分子在叙利亚东部越狱，导致与美国支持的叙利亚军队进行了数天的巷战。大约 500 人在暴力事件中死亡。</p><p>伊斯兰国已无法重拾昔日在叙利亚和伊拉克的势头，但也在阿富汗和非洲部分地区设有分支机构。</p><p>该组织仍然面临着美国领导的叙利亚和伊拉克联军的压力。 7月，美国军方表示，他们在叙利亚的一次空袭中打死了一名伊斯兰国领导人。</p><p>该组织的前任高级领导人于 2022 年在一次与美国无关的行动中被叙利亚武装分子杀害。另一名高级领导人于 2022 年初在美国突击队的一次突袭中被杀。</p><p>写信给 Jared Malsin： <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jared.malsin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 18:57:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/islamic-state-confirms-top-leader-is-dead-dfc114a3<author><![CDATA[Jared Malsin]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What Is Happening in Niger? What to Know About the Coup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国西非反恐盟友民选总统下台引发军事干预威胁<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829069/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>军政府政变的支持者在尼日尔首都尼亚美集会。法新社/盖蒂图片社<span>法新社/盖蒂图片社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107681"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 3 日下午 2:34（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>尼日尔精锐总统卫队官员上周<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拘留了这个西非国家的民选总统</a>穆罕默德·巴祖姆，并宣布自己为该国新领导人。这次政变令美国和欧洲政府感到震惊，这些国家一直与巴祖姆和尼日尔军队密切合作，打击非洲萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。</p><p>尼日尔的一些西非邻国（主要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国和欧洲结盟</a>）威胁要使用武力恢复巴祖姆的地位。其他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯结盟的</a>国家则表示，他们将捍卫尼日尔的新军政府。</p><h3>美国和欧洲政府为何担心尼日尔政变？</h3><p>尼日尔一直是美国和欧洲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">打击基地组织和伊斯兰国武装分子</a>的中心，这些武装分子近年来在撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区萨赫勒地区杀害了数千人。在马里和布基纳法索军方领导的政府驱逐了一直在那里与伊斯兰叛乱分子作战的法国和其他西方军队后，尼日尔变得更加重要。美国已花费约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，配备从帐篷、收音机到侦察机和装甲运兵车等各种装备。美国在尼日尔驻有约 1,100 名士兵，他们训练当地特种部队并为他们执行任务提供建议。法国在尼日尔驻有大约 1,500 名士兵。</p><p>欧盟还依赖世界上最贫穷国家之一的尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-considers-substantial-fund-for-africa-to-deal-with-migrants-1440871414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来阻止非洲移民</a>进入利比亚并从那里进入欧盟。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="819" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828956?width=1260&amp;height=819" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">政变支持者在尼亚美示威期间悬挂俄罗斯国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>什么是西共体？它能扭转政变吗？</h3><p>西非国家经济共同体是一个由 15 个西非国家组成的政治和经济组织，其中包括尼日利亚、加纳和塞内加尔等地区重量级国家。周日，西非经共体领导人在一次紧急峰会上给尼日尔新军政府规定了 7 天的期限，以释放巴祖姆并让他重新担任总统。此后，该组织领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁要对尼日尔发动军事干预</a>，以恢复巴祖姆的权力。他们还对尼日尔实施了一系列严厉的金融和贸易制裁，希望迫使军政府做出让步。这些制裁包括冻结尼日尔在地区中央银行的资产以及切断尼日利亚的电力供应。尼日尔约 70% 的电力从尼日利亚购买。</p><p>作为回应，马里和布基纳法索的政变也受到西非经共体的谴责，它们警告说，他们将把对尼日尔的武装干预视为宣战，并将保卫尼亚美军政府。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828965?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲和美国公民从尼日尔撤离后抵达罗马附近的机场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雷莫·卡西利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>美国如何回应？</h3><p>拜登总统和国务卿安东尼·布林肯呼吁释放巴祖姆并保护尼日尔的民主。然而，美国官员一直小心翼翼地避免将军方的行动称为政变，这一名称将引发美国法律<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对军事援助的限制</a>。国防部表示，没有计划将军事人员或装备撤出尼日尔，并支持通过外交途径解决局势。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=2AE037D3-6705-43B5-828C-C117387FADDD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔上周发生政变后，欧洲各国政府和美国下令从尼日尔撤离本国公民。军政府领导人表示，军方不会屈服于压力，要求让被罢黜的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆复职。照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>拜登政府尚未表示美国是否会为西非经共体可能对尼日尔进行的军事干预提供后勤或其他支持。 “我们支持西非经共体的努力，包括施加压力，”布林肯周四表示。美国国务院已下令<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">撤离美国驻尼亚美大使馆的所有非必要人员</a>以及美国大使馆工作人员的家属。</p><p>与法国不同的是，美国尚未从尼日尔全面撤离美国公民。法国本周向尼日尔派遣了多架撤侨航班，并表示已帮助约 40 名美国公民离开该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828970?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆与美国和欧洲政府密切合作，打击伊斯兰激进分子。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路透社/媒体库</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>俄罗斯对尼日尔政变持何立场？</strong></h3><p>俄罗斯政府呼吁尼日尔恢复宪法秩序，并警告不要进行武装干预。叶夫根尼·普里戈任,</p>他的准军事瓦格纳集团已经在马里拥有战士，他赞扬了这次政变，并向尼亚美军政府提供了雇佣军服务。<p></p><p>法国外交部长本周将周末针对法国大使馆的支持政变抗议活动归咎于俄罗斯的虚假信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="390" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829050?width=700&amp;height=390" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">军政府首脑、尼日尔自称领导人奥马尔·查尼将军率领总统卫队发动了政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ORTN/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>奥马尔·奇亚尼将军是谁？</h3><p>奥马尔·齐亚尼将军，有时也被称为阿卜杜拉哈马内，是发动反对巴祖姆起义的总统卫队队长。他现在作为尼日尔自封的领导人领导军政府。据熟悉尼日尔局势的人士透露，巴祖姆一直在考虑是否解雇蒂亚尼，这是政变的触发因素之一。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——威廉·莫尔丁对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟 (Gabriele Steinhauser)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 18:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc<author><![CDATA[Gabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>奥马尔·齐亚尼</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[India Restricts Laptop Imports to Boost Local Manufacturing]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该国笔记本电脑销售的很大一部分依赖进口，其中许多来自竞争对手中国<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107307"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828990?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">印度此举被视为旨在说服更多全球电子制造商签署其“印度制造”计划。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：普拉卡什·辛格/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107307"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rajesh-roy" itemprop="url" rel="author">拉杰什·罗伊</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 11:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-restricts-laptop-imports-to-boost-local-manufacturing-244cf56a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>新德里——政府和行业官员表示，印度正在加大进口笔记本电脑、平板电脑和其他消费电子设备的难度，此举旨在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-u-s-and-modi-rewire-indian-defense-and-tech-dfabec47?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">促进当地制造业</a>并解决一些安全问题。</p><p>印度商业和工业部周四表示，笔记本电脑和其他个人计算设备的进口现在需要许可证，这使得进口过程变得更加繁琐。</p><p> “其中一些进口产品的硬件安全性令人担忧。因此，为了印度的数字安全利益，我们采取了这一步骤。”一位直接了解此事的印度政府官员表示。 “这样做的后果也可能是这些公司开始考虑本地制造。”</p><p>人们普遍认为此举旨在让更多的全球电子产品制造商加入该国的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-offers-1-billion-in-perks-to-entice-computer-makers-from-china-11614171742?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">“印度制造”计划</a>，该计划为本地制造电子产品和其他高科技产品提供激励，符合条件的公司将收回数百万美元的投资。该国最初将该计划针对智能手机，后来将其扩展到其他领域，包括无人机<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foxconn-abandons-india-chip-venture-with-vedanta-e11a8687?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">、半导体</a>以及科技硬件。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>根据官方数据，2022 年 1 月至 12 月，新限制范围内的计算机和服务器等计算设备的进口总额接近 100 亿美元，约占印度去年进口总额的 1.4%。</p><p>印度目前没有知名的本地个人电脑制造商，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HPQ" class="company-name">惠普</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DELL" class="company-name">戴尔科技</a>等跨国公司目前在当地的生产数量有限。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">苹果</a>通过其合同制造商在印度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-opens-its-first-retail-store-in-india-7f3a7035?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">生产越来越多的 iPhone</a> ，但尚未在该国生产<span class="company-name-type">MacBook</span>或 iPad。</p><p> Counterpoint Research 总监塔伦·帕塔克 (Tarun Pathak) 表示，印度在智能手机和电视几乎 100% 本地制造方面取得了显着进展，但在 IT 硬件领域，约三分之二的销售额依赖进口。</p><p>戴尔根据该计划的早期版本申请了获得本地笔记本电脑制造奖励的资格。今年 5 月，政府将用于制造 IT 硬件的资金扩大到约 20 亿美元，涵盖笔记本电脑、平板电脑、一体化个人电脑和服务器，以期与更多跨国公司签约。本周，它将制造商根据该计划提出申请的截止日期延长至 8 月 30 日。</p><p>印度还出台了关税或其他进口限制的激励措施，行业高管和分析师表示，鉴于许多类型的电子产品和零部件的本地制造尚未扩大规模，这可能会影响制造商和消费者。</p><p> “这是政府的下意识反应。工业正处于修复之中。他们应该首先与我们进行一些协商，而不是立即限制进口，”一家也销售平板电脑和笔记本电脑的领先消费电子公司的高管表示。 “这将影响业务连续性。”</p><p> Counterpoint 的帕塔克表示，这些限制可能会在短期内导致供应中断，尤其是随着节日购物季的临近。Counterpoint 的数据显示，印度年度个人电脑市场规模约为 80 亿美元。</p><p>惠普引领印度个人电脑销售市场，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LNVGY" class="company-name">联想</a>紧随其后</p>根据市场研究公司 IDC 的数据，中国。印度近年来一直寻求减少对竞争对手中国的进口依赖，特别是在 2020 年 6 月两国有争议的喜马拉雅边境爆发暴力冲突、造成 20 名印度士兵和 4 名中国士兵死亡之后。<p></p><p>官员和行业高管表示，激励计划已经促进了印度科技制造业的发展。 4月至6月的贸易数据显示，尽管整体出口下降，但电子产品出口（尤其是智能手机）大幅增长。</p><p>写信给 Rajesh Roy，邮箱： <a href="mailto:rajesh.roy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rajesh.roy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 15:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-restricts-laptop-imports-to-boost-local-manufacturing-244cf56a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-restricts-laptop-imports-to-boost-local-manufacturing-244cf56a<author><![CDATA[Rajesh Roy]]></author><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>便携式电脑</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>企业/行业进口</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>戴尔科技集团 C</category><category>戴尔</category><category>联想集团</category><category>0992.HK</category><category>港币:992</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>销售数据</category><category>公司的</category><category>工业进口</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>便携式电脑</category><category>计算</category><category>电脑硬件</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Rags-to-Riches Female Candidate Shakes Up Mexico Presidential Race]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>小时候卖玉米粉蒸肉的索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 与总统洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔 (López Obrador) 发生争执，并为沮丧的反对派提供鼓励<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828458/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="霍奇特尔·加尔维斯最近在蒂华纳竞选，在墨西哥反对派联盟总统提名的竞选中处于领先地位。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>霍奇特尔·加尔韦斯最近在蒂华纳竞选，在墨西哥反对派联盟总统提名的竞选中处于领先地位。桑迪·赫法克 (Sandy Huffaker) 供职于《华尔街日报》<span>桑迪·赫法克 (Sandy Huffaker) 供职于《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105162"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105162"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jose-decordoba" itemprop="url" rel="author">何塞·德·科尔多瓦</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-montes" itemprop="url" rel="author">胡安·蒙特斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>墨西哥库埃纳瓦卡——Xóchitl Gálvez 穿着长及脚踝的传统土著服饰，大步走进挤满人的礼堂，商界人士起立鼓掌，高呼“Xóchitl”！霍奇特尔！</p><p>自六月参加墨西哥总统竞选以来，60 岁的加尔韦斯似乎让沮丧的反对派兴奋不已，并使总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔感到不安，他的执政党莫雷纳党预计将在明年的总统选举中轻松获胜，凭借民众的支持领导的燕尾服。</p><p>几周之内，加尔韦斯就将自己定位为十几个赢得墨西哥反对派联盟提名的候选人中明显的领跑者。候选人将于 9 月 3 日初选后确定。</p><p>洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔不再参选是因为<strong>&nbsp;</strong>墨西哥不允许连任。他很可能会祝福墨西哥城前市长克劳迪娅·谢因鲍姆，后者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexican-presidential-hopefuls-kick-off-race-to-succeed-lopez-obrador-70b16467?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">有望赢得党内提名</a>。在民意调查中，她领先莫雷纳的另一位希望之星、前外交部长马塞洛·埃布拉德(Marcelo Ebrard)约10个百分点。</p><p>反对派选民<strong>&nbsp;</strong>在加尔韦斯介入之前，他已经接受了莫雷纳在 2024 年选举中取得压倒性胜利。</p><p>这位鲜为人知的参议员经常骑着电动自行车出行，她有一个引人入胜的个人故事，从年轻女孩的街头小贩成长为成功的女商人和当选官员。她的支持者说，她传达的妇女权利、支持墨西哥人民对美好生活的渴望以及民族团结的信息，给因洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的分裂政治而疲惫不堪的墨西哥人带来了希望。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="816" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828495?width=1260&amp;height=816" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Xóchitl Gálvez 骑着自行车游览墨西哥城。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿尔弗雷多·埃斯特雷拉/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828461?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 的平易近人的举止、朴实的语言和对戏剧手势的喜爱吸引了普通墨西哥人。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的桑迪·赫法克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>墨西哥政治分析人士表示，加尔韦斯最近在民调中的支持率上升很大程度上要归功于洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔本人，他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/think-u-s-politics-is-exhausting-mexicos-president-has-a-news-conference-every-morning-11565626849?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">每天都在早间新闻发布会上猛烈抨击她</a>，嘲笑她自力更生的故事，并提高了她在全国的知名度。</p><p>民意调查专家尤利塞斯·贝尔特兰 (Ulises Beltrán) 表示：“她是一个引人注目的现象。”他指出，她以两位数的优势领先最接近的反对派竞争者。</p><p>洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的发言人否认总统在政治上提振了加尔维斯，并将她的崛起归因于媒体的有利报道。他拒绝对总统竞选发表评论。</p><p>正在寻求提名的执政党成员、前参议员里卡多·蒙雷亚尔表示，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔发表有关加尔韦斯的言论是为了动员他的政治基础。</p><p> “他把差异说得一清二楚是正确的，”他说。</p><p>虽然加尔韦斯作为一名女商人的成功吸引了墨西哥的政治和经济机构，但她平易近人的举止、朴实的语言和对戏剧手势的喜爱却赢得了普通墨西哥人的青睐。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/3e8d3948-b604-4789-979f-3b0c2356e368.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xbgzW1zoD8k" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">她戴着银色假发，头戴白色瓜亚贝拉，在 2018 年的一段视频中模仿了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔</a>，该视频在 YouTube 上获得了数万次观看。去年，她穿着绿色霸王龙服装冲进参议院，抗议洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔提议的选举改革，她说这将使墨西哥“回到侏罗纪时代”。</p><p>加尔韦斯（Gálvez）的名字 Xóchitl 发音为“SOH-cheel”，在纳瓦特尔语中意为“花”，他的父亲是土著奥托米人，母亲是混血儿妇女，出生在特帕佩克（Tepatepec）。特帕佩克是一个昏昏欲睡的小镇，约有 11,000 人，周围环绕着郁郁葱葱的玉米地，车程约两小时。 &#39; 从墨西哥城开车过来。</p><p>加尔维斯说，她酗酒的父亲（现已去世）经常殴打她的母亲，有一次威胁要用猎枪射击母亲后，半夜将妻子和女儿赶出了家门。</p><p>她的表弟拉蒙·加尔韦斯 (Ramón Gálvez) 说，小时候，她与父母和四个兄弟姐妹睡在距离镇主广场几个街区的一栋单层土坯房的同一个房间里。房子没有自来水，一家人不得不收集雨水。他们与住在另外两个房间的七名亲戚共用一个厕所。</p><p> “这是一种充满暴力和贫困的生活，”她说。加尔维斯说，为了维持生计，她帮助母亲在街上卖果冻和玉米粉蒸肉。她说，当她父亲反对她读六年级以上时，她反抗了他。</p><p> “如果有什么东西定义了她，那就是她渴望变得更好，”表弟马可·安东尼奥·鲁伊斯说。</p><p> 17 岁时，加尔韦斯离开特帕佩克，来到墨西哥城贫民区的一间金属板搭建的单间小屋。她在接受采访时说，她早上担任电话接线员，晚上在墨西哥国立自治大学学习工程学，并在那里获得了奖学金。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="814" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828562?width=1260&amp;height=814" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总统安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的政党有望赢得下次选举。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：isaac esquivel/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="805" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828463?width=1260&amp;height=805" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯 (Xóchitl Gálvez) 的一位支持者在最近的一次竞选集会上举着一块牌子，上面写着“Xambeadora”，这是墨西哥“勤奋者”一词与她名字的组合。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的桑迪·赫法克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>由于对计算的着迷，她创立了一家为智能建筑提供设备的高科技公司。 1999年，她被列入世界经济论坛的100位未来全球领导人名单。第二年，猎头公司向总统文森特·福克斯推荐她领导一个土著事务研究所，她一直担任到 2006 年。</p><p> 2018 年，她成为保守派国家行动党 (PAN) 的参议员，尽管她不是党员。</p><p> “她的人生故事超越了墨西哥国家故事的任何戏剧性剧本，”参议员同事、国家行动党前主席古斯塔沃·马德罗说。</p><p>民意调查专家贝尔特兰表示，加尔韦斯作为候选人的优势在于，她颠覆了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔对反对派的讽刺，认为后者代表了富裕、腐败和保守的寡头政治。</p><p> “信息就是信使，”政治分析家、墨西哥前外交部长豪尔赫·卡斯塔涅达 (Jorge Castañeda) 说。 “她让洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的身份政治对他有利。”</p><p>民意调查专家亚历杭德罗·莫雷诺表示，加尔韦斯还吸引了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔政党的传统选民。 “她对女性、老年人和受教育程度较低的人很有吸引力，”他说。</p><p>尽管如此，在 El Financiero 报纸最近的一项民意调查中，加尔维斯仍落后 Sheinbaum 10 个百分点。</p><p>加尔维斯表示，她支持总统的社会计划，但认为这些计划应该更加有效。她认为自己的个人故事是对洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔对像她这样的墨西哥奋斗者的蔑视的谴责。</p><p>在总统透露了洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔公司合同的财务数据后，加尔韦斯对洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔提起了两项刑事诉讼。她说这些数据包括机密的税务信息，她说这些信息是非法获得的。洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔没有透露它来自哪里。他的发言人表示，法官将确定洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔是否做了不当或非法的事情。</p><p>加尔维斯偶尔会用墨西哥俚语和咯咯的笑声来反驳洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔的攻击。</p><p> “他是个大男子主义，我一生中和很多大男子主义打过交道，”她说。</p><p>六月，在他错误地表示她想拿走老人的养老金后，她要求他道歉。在他拒绝后，她向法院提起诉讼，并获得裁决，赋予她在同一论坛上作出答复的权利。</p><p> “我不会在战斗中退缩。当他向我提出质疑时，我就上了法庭，”她说。</p><p>拿着法院命令，加尔维斯骑着自行车前往总统府，洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔正在那里举行上午的新闻发布会。她敲了敲宫殿的厚重木门，但总统拒绝让她进去。加尔韦斯最终离开了。</p><p>她的失败尝试赢得了大批支持，促使她认真考虑竞选总统。两周后，她宣布参选。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828487?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">索奇特尔·加尔韦斯关于妇女权利、支持苦苦挣扎的墨西哥人对美好生活的渴望以及民族团结的信息引起了一些墨西哥人的共鸣。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：卡洛斯·莫雷诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 José de Córdoba <a href="mailto:jose.decordoba@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(jose.decordoba@wsj.com)</a>和 Juan Montes ( <a href="mailto:juan.montes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">juan.montes@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/rags-to-riches-female-candidate-shakes-up-mexico-presidential-race-abf1ba86<author><![CDATA[José de CórdobaJuan Montes]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>家庭暴力</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>霍奇特尔·加尔韦斯</category><category>安德烈斯·曼努埃尔·洛佩斯·奥夫拉多尔</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>家庭暴力</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Tragedy of Being a New Mom in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国五分之一的母亲在怀孕期间或出生后不久患有情绪和焦虑症。对于许多人来说，很难找到帮助。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828284/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="俄亥俄州帕尔马市的贾克琳·奥默 (Jaclyn Ohmer) 抱着她的儿子。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>俄亥俄州帕尔马市的贾克琳·奥默 (Jaclyn Ohmer) 抱着她的儿子。华尔街日报的麦迪·麦加维<span>华尔街日报的麦迪·麦加维</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105248"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105248"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anna-mutoh" itemprop="url" rel="author">武藤安娜</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 8:02 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mothers-mental-health-women-postpartum-depression-7b548f43"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>贾克琳·奥默 (Jaclyn Ohmer) 迫不及待地想要生孩子。在她怀孕之前，她买了连体衣和小猎犬形状的靴子。她和她的高中恋人丈夫发现他们有了一个儿子，并准备了一个星球大战主题的婴儿房。这位来自俄亥俄州帕尔马的 26 岁年轻人已经为他的到来做好了准备。</p><p>去年六月他出生后，事情变得更加困难。欧默爱他，但她常常感到悲伤。她焦急地等待着他的下一次哭声。她不确定自己是否适合当妈妈。</p><p>有一天，当奥默尖叫时，他产生了一个可怕的想法：“如果我把手放在他的嘴上，他就会消失。他不必和我住在一起，也不必经历这一切。”</p><p>她越来越害怕伤害她的孩子，并且更加相信没有她，她的家人会过得更好。欧默试图寻求帮助，但很难找到帮助。</p><p>研究人员估计，美国五分之一的新妈妈在怀孕期间和产后一年内患有情绪和焦虑障碍——每年约有 800,000 名妈妈。然而研究表明，绝大多数患有产妇心理健康障碍的女性无法获得帮助。</p><p>一个主要原因是美国医疗保健系统的零碎性质，没有任何医疗专业人员对新妈妈及其心理健康负责。产科医生通常是新妈妈的第一个医疗联系人，但通常并不擅长于此。儿科医生专注于儿童。许多寻求帮助的女性不断寻求医生的帮助，但在心理健康专家短缺的情况下，她们很难找到治疗方法。</p><p> “产科医生可能不会拥有所有权。儿科医生不得拥有所有权。精神科医生可能不会拥有所有权，”非营利组织孕产妇心理健康政策中心的创始人乔伊·伯克哈德说。 “他们所有人都把母亲推向对方，而母亲却被忽视了。”</p><p>根据世界卫生组织的数据，美国已经是高收入国家中分娩<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-maternal-mortality-hits-highest-level-since-1965-f9829776?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最危险的</a>国家，与怀孕和分娩相关的死亡率最高。根据国家卫生统计中心的数据，美国怀孕期间或怀孕后不久死亡的妇女人数达到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-maternal-mortality-hits-highest-level-since-1965-f9829776?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">1965 年以来的最高水平</a>，达到每 10 万活产 33 人死亡，这一数字仅次于叙利亚和乌兹别克斯坦。</p><p>去年九月，美国疾病控制与预防中心表示，精神健康障碍已成为孕产妇死亡的主要原因，导致近四分之一的妊娠相关死亡。其中包括在怀孕期间或出生后一年内因自杀和吸毒过量而死亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828530?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥默在医生和医院之间穿梭寻求帮助。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>已被证明对孕产妇心理健康有效的治疗方法（例如心理治疗）很难获得。 New mothers can also face the stigma of being seen as an unfit parent and have their baby taken away, leaving some reluctant to seek help.</p><p> This week, the Food and Drug Administration is expected to announce a decision on zuranolone, the first pill to treat postpartum depression. If approved, the challenge “will be in making sure people can access it. Because that is the piece that new medication does not solve,” said Dr. Nancy Byatt, a perinatal psychiatrist at UMass Chan Medical School.</p><p> In the struggle to find treatment, Ohmer was no exception.</p><p> Ohmer told her obstetrician at University Hospitals Health System that she often felt sad and anxious. Her OB said those feelings were normal for a new mother, and prescribed her anxiety medication.</p><p> Days later, Ohmer called her husband at work in a panic. She was having suicidal thoughts. Her OB sent her to the emergency room.</p><p> The ER didn&#39;t admit her because Ohmer didn&#39;t have a specific plan to end her life, according to Ohmer and her family. Instead, they told her to go see her primary care doctor at Cleveland Clinic, who set her up with a social worker. The social worker recommended an outpatient postpartum depression care center not affiliated with Cleveland Clinic. It had a one-year wait list.</p><p> Ohmer&#39;s anxiety worsened over the next two months, leading to nightly panic attacks and regular hallucinations. She found herself shuttled between doctors and hospitals. She repeatedly tried to overdose on her anxiety medication. She felt ashamed when an ER nurse suggested she was selfish to have attempted suicide. She was eventually sent for both inpatient and outpatient care at Highland Springs, a general behavioral health facility near Cleveland.</p><p> She went for a month, but said she didn&#39;t feel any better. “Nobody in there could relate to her and talk to her about what she was going through,” said Tiffany McBroom, 51, Ohmer&#39;s mother.</p><p> University Hospitals, Cleveland Clinic and Highland Springs declined to comment, citing patient privacy.</p><p> “The whole time, we&#39;re trusting all these doctors with everyone saying, &#39;Oh, yeah, we&#39;re gonna help you,&#39; but every time it&#39;s been a letdown,” said Nick Ohmer, 25, Ohmer&#39;s husband.</p><h3> Potential causes</h3><p> Scientists aren&#39;t sure what causes postpartum depression and associated mood disorders, but one potential cause could be some women&#39;s sensitivity to fluctuating hormones. A recent study from the <a href="https://news.unchealthcare.org/2023/02/researchers-uncover-mechanisms-of-brexanolone-and-the-role-of-inflammation-in-post-partum-depression/" target="_blank" class="icon none">University of North Carolina School of Medicine</a> suggests inflammation in neural pathways may contribute to the syndrome.</p><p> A growing number of Americans have been diagnosed with mental-health disorders, due in part to factors like increased screening and the toll of the pandemic. But therapists are in short supply. The shortage is even worse for those who focus on new mothers, doctors say. A new field called reproductive psychiatry, which focuses on issues related to women and childbearing, remains relatively unknown even among medical professionals.</p><p> Across the country, there are only <a href="https://www.postpartum.net/get-help/intensive-perinatal-psych-treatment-in-the-us/" target="_blank" class="icon none">three</a> inpatient care facilities dedicated to maternal mental-health care, according to Postpartum Support International, a nonprofit organization, and nearly 30 more that offer outpatient care.</p><p> Brenda Encarnacion, 30, from Santa Clarita, Calif., was voted Most Likely to Know Everyone in high school. She had been working as an extra in movies but became a federal deportation officer because she wanted more financial stability so she could start a family with her husband, Mitchail Encarnacion, 31.</p><p> After their baby girl was born in October 2020, some friends said they saw a change in her mood, but thought it was normal stress. “She was hiding it very well,” her father, Miguel Ayala, 57, said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828581?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Miguel Ayala holds a photo of his daughter, Brenda Encarnacion.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carlos Jaramillo for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Mitchail Encarnacion noticed changes after three months when his wife stopped breast-feeding and she returned to work after maxing out her unpaid 12-week family leave. She would start crying while baking a pie or simply because she wore the “wrong pants,” he said.</p><p> A trained paramedic, he noticed bruise marks on her legs, and one day saw his wife punching her limbs. He begged her to go see a therapist, he said. She began to see a general therapist once a week but stopped when she didn&#39;t find it helpful.</p><p> At each pediatric visit for their daughter, staff routinely asked if she was feeling depressed or had suicidal thoughts, her husband said, but he didn&#39;t feel staff members were really engaging with her. “It was not even like a second, and obviously Brenda&#39;s going to be like, &#39;No.&#39;”</p><p> One day Brenda told her husband that she felt worthless—a sign that suggested she might be having suicidal thoughts, he said. He tried to convince her to leave her job, but they got into an argument because that would mean losing their health insurance.</p><p> The following morning, at around 5 am, Mitchail woke up to a text from Brenda. She apologized and cryptically told him she left so he couldn&#39;t stop her, he said. She told him that she loved him, and to make sure their daughter knew she loved her too. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/fc3e6dc4-5758-4d38-9fa5-2d382d136caf.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In a panic, Mitchail rushed to the local train station that Brenda used for her commute. Her car was there, engine running, and the door unlocked.</p><p> He opened the car door and found his wife inside, dead.</p><p> “She shot herself in the heart,” said Brenda&#39;s father, Ayala.</p><p> Later that day, a package of hundreds of printed photos, downloaded from Brenda&#39;s phone, arrived at the family&#39;s home, Mitchail said—sent by his wife.</p><p> Reasons for suicide are rarely clear or simple. Brenda had kept a lot to herself, said Jeriann Ledner, 32, one of her closest friends. “I have come to terms that she had the disease of postpartum depression, because that is not something that the Brenda we loved would have done,” she said.</p><p> Her husband said he&#39;s now living with his parents, who help him take care of their daughter, and thinks every day about how he could have prevented his wife&#39;s suicide. He said he has since been diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder, anxiety and severe depression.</p><p> Women who attempt suicide typically overdose or cut themselves, both of which can be reversed if caught in time, said Adrienne Griffen, founder of Maternal Mental Health Leadership Alliance, a nonprofit organization focused on health policy. Women who have recently given birth, however, often choose more lethal means of death, including jumping, hanging and shooting. “They are so desperate,” she said.</p><h3> Higher risk</h3><p> The US is the only high-income nation in the world that doesn&#39;t have paid maternity leave, according to the nonprofit Bipartisan Policy Center, and an estimated one in four women return to work within two weeks of giving birth. The stress of juggling a job during the physical and emotional changes of new motherhood puts women at higher risk for postpartum depression, studies have found.</p><p> The statistics are worse for Black women in the US According to the National Center for Health Statistics, their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-maternal-mortality-hits-highest-level-since-1965-f9829776?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mortality rate</a> was 2.6 times as much as the rate for white women. Public-health experts have attributed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sprinter-tori-bowies-death-reflects-maternal-mortality-crisis-f88d0d8?mod=WTRN_pos2&amp;cx_testId=3&amp;cx_testVariant=cx_160&amp;cx_artPos=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the disparity</a> in part to less access to healthcare, fewer economic and educational opportunities that contribute to maternal health and unintentional bias among healthcare workers.</p><p> Studies have found that Black mothers are more likely than white mothers to suffer from maternal mental-health disorders, and less likely to get help. Black women who do seek help are often labeled angry and emotional, said Da&#39;na Langford, co-founder of Village of Healing, an Ohio maternal-health care provider run by Black women. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828587?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Denise Williams was &#39;bubbly and could light up the room,&#39; said her sister.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Shane Williams</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Only 5% of psychologists and 6% of psychiatrists are Black, according to industry groups.</p><p> Belinda Staley in New York said the stigma and difficulty of getting help had an impact on her sister, Denise Williams, a former supervisor at Costco and a single mother of two young daughters. Williams was “bubbly and could light up the room,” said her sister, adding, “There was nothing Denise wouldn&#39;t do for her babies.”</p><p> About a year after her first daughter was born in 2018, Williams began to change, Staley said, secluding herself in her room for hours at a time. Then she started asking, “Am I a great mom?” Staley said.</p><p> Williams&#39; apparent depression grew worse when she was pregnant with her second child, Staley said. At times, she would wander outside at 2 am with her toddler, said Charlene Magee, 50, Williams&#39; aunt.</p><p> In 2021, when Williams was about six months pregnant with her second daughter, she went to a police station across the street seeking help and was sent to a hospital psychiatric ward for two weeks, Staley said.</p><p> Putting a woman with a maternal mental-health disorder into a general psychiatric ward is “like offering headache medication to somebody with a stomachache,” said Kallen Thornton, manager of Gender Responsive Services at the Colorado Behavioral Health Administration, a state agency. In addition, she said, “It can damage her identity as a mother and motivation for recovery.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827755?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Belinda Staley; her mother, Linda Magee; and her late sister&#39;s two daughters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Gabriela Bhaskar for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Williams had her second child a few months later. After she told a drugstore employee she wanted to kill herself and her children, emergency medical services took her to a hospital where she was handcuffed, shackled and labeled a prisoner under arrest in need of medical care, according to medical records. New York&#39;s child protective services took her children, and temporary custody was given to her sister. Williams was discharged three days later.</p><p> Ten days later, Williams&#39; mother called an ambulance because Williams was acting erratically. She died at the hospital two days later, at age 29. The autopsy report said she had died of a pulmonary embolism, a blood clot that travels to the lungs.</p><p> Looking back at how Williams was treated, Staley said, “the help wasn&#39;t there for my sister.”</p><p> Ohmer finally found help at the University of North Carolina Chapel Hill&#39;s Center for Women&#39;s Mood Disorders, one of the three inpatient facilities in the US for maternal mental health.</p><p> While such facilities have existed in other countries for over 60 years, UNC was the first to open specialized inpatient care in the US in 2011, said Dr. Samantha Meltzer-Brody, department chair of the center.</p><p> Two weeks after she got in touch with UNC, Ohmer, her husband and her mother drove the nine hours from Ohio to North Carolina. She was told she would stay anywhere between a week and 20 days. “What if the baby forgets who I am?”她想知道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828225?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ohmer and her husband play with their son at home.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Maddie McGarvey for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Within a week, Ohmer passed an evaluation process to get brexanolone, the first drug approved by the FDA in 2019 specifically for postpartum depression. The 60-hour intravenous infusion treatment is made from a derivative of the hormone progesterone.</p><p> Patients need to be monitored during treatment because it can cause <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK541054/" target="_blank" class="icon none">excessive sedation and sudden loss of consciousness</a> , but it can start working within days. Speed of recovery is especially important for new mothers to achieve baby bonding, doctors say.</p><p> Without insurance, Ohmer&#39;s total treatment cost for three weeks at UNC, including the infusion and other therapy, would have been over $180,000. With insurance, she paid just under $1,500. The bill still added to the thousands of dollars in medical debt the family had accumulated.</p><p> After two days of the treatment, Ohmer&#39;s family noticed a difference. “Her voice had a lightness,” said her mother.</p><p> Ohmer said she is still working through her mental-health challenges, but they feel much more manageable.</p><p> “Nobody cares about the mental state of moms until you hear about it on the news when they&#39;re already gone or the baby is gone,” she said. “The lack of care, I just don&#39;t understand.”</p><p> <em>Help is available: Call or text the <a href="https://mchb.hrsa.gov/national-maternal-mental-health-hotline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The National Maternal Mental Health Hotline</a> at 1-833-TLC-MAMA (1-833-852-6262). You can also reach the <a href="https://988lifeline.org/" target="_blank" class="icon none">988 Suicide &amp; Crisis Lifeline</a> (formerly known as the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline) by dialing or texting 988.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 12:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mothers-mental-health-women-postpartum-depression-7b548f43</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mothers-mental-health-women-postpartum-depression-7b548f43<author><![CDATA[Anna Mutoh]]></author><category>摄影委托</category><category>领导者</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Mood Disorders</category><category> Demographic Health</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>精神错乱</category><category>Women&#39;s Health</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>mood disorders</category><category> demographic health</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>mental disorders</category><category> women&#39;s health </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israeli Reservists Start Missing Duty, Threatening Military Unity and Readiness]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>拒绝任职是改革司法机构的努力如何导致国家分裂的最明显例子之一<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106909"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828271?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列空军学员在毕业典礼上。飞行训练因教官抗议而中断。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ariel Schalit/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001106909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 6:50 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——上校尼西姆·约格夫 (Nissim Yogev) 在以色列空军担任战斗飞行领航员 25 年，参加了以色列与黎巴嫩的战争，亲眼目睹他最好的朋友在战斗中失踪，再也没有回来。上周，他说他做出了一生中最艰难的决定，当时他泪流满面地写信给他的指挥官，表示他将停止报到志愿预备役，他在空军唯一的飞行学校训练学员。</p><p> “没有我，飞行学校可能会过得很好，但只要事情继续这样下去，我就不能接受自己，”他写道。</p><p> 64岁的约格夫上周缺席了第一天的教学，当时他正在执行数千名像他一样的志愿预备役军人的威胁，在以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的联盟<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通过了限制权力努力的第一部分</a>后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-overhaul-raises-security-concerns-as-reservists-refuse-to-serve-5d68bfff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，他将暂停服役。</a>最高法院。</p><p> The reservists say <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the legislation</a> undermines Israel&#39;s liberal democracy, breaking the social contract for which they have put their lives at risk.组织推动拒绝服役的最大团体之一的“兄弟连”表示，已经有数千人像约格夫一样拒绝服预备役。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828288?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Col. Nissim Yogev, in white shirt, with a friend who went missing in action in 1986.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：尼西姆·约格夫</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>目前还不清楚有多少像尤格夫这样的预备役军人已经错过了他们应该服役的日子。但有迹象表明，军方已经感受到了损失。一位知情人士称，在最近的至少一期飞行员培训课程中，几乎没有教员到场值班。这个问题变得如此尖锐，以至于飞行训练学校的负责人上周致函学员家长，表示训练仍在继续，尽管许多教官尚未出现。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡表示，预备役抗议是不民主的。士兵们试图向政府发号施令。他的联盟中的一些人称这是一次未遂的军事政变。 The coalition says it is enacting policies favored by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its voters</a> who say <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-government-looks-at-next-steps-in-judicial-overhaul-shrugging-off-protests-7172e0ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the top court</a> is controlled by liberal justices who too quickly overturn the will of the people.他们说，这项立法旨在恢复政府不同部门之间的适当权力平衡。</p><p>预备役军人的抗议是内塔尼亚胡推动司法机构改革如何导致国家分裂的最明显例子之一。以色列军队长期以来一直是分裂社会的团结力量，对于这个自 75 年前建国以来一直深陷冲突的国家至关重要。</p><p>团结的削弱可能会损害以色列军队赖以生存的人民军队模式，而这种模式近年来已经<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-israel-army-service-is-required-for-all-that-could-now-change-2c76624d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">面临压力</a>。 It could also harm the military in more immediate ways, affecting operational readiness if reservists&#39; skills become outdated. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828273?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has pushed ahead with judicial overhauls despite large-scale protests.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>以色列国防部长约阿夫·加兰特在本周的议会委员会会议上表示：“对健康的损害是有限的，但从长远来看，有可能对健康造成损害。”</p><p>同样在本周，以色列军事参谋长与每一位上校及以上级别的军官举行了小组会议，讨论如何处理军队内部的政治分歧，因为这些师已经渗透到正规队伍中。</p><p> Israel&#39;s military has hundreds of thousands of reservists, some 120,000 of whom are in active reserve duty between the ages of 22 and 45, according to statements by a senior military officer in May of 2022. Those above the age of active reserve duty can continue to volunteer for reserve duty, and some—like Yogev—hold positions that require their service on a weekly or biweekly basis and have their days of duty scheduled in advance.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>空军飞行教官的抗议将对以色列的司法改革产生什么影响？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>像尤格夫这样的飞行学院教练会提前几个月报名参加教学，并且预计会在需要时在短时间内赶到。 He said he missed his first day of teaching at the end of July and won&#39;t show up for his next scheduled teaching day in mid-August.</p><p> 47 岁的埃亚勒·纳维 (Eyal Naveh) 是以色列最精锐的突击队 Sayeret Matkal 的预备役军官，也是兄弟连抗议组织的领导人。他们不会上班的人。纳维说，他们包括情报和网络专家，以及海军预备役司令部的成员。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828279?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列预备役军人在特拉维夫的抗议活动中签署拒绝服役的声明。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Eyal Warshavsky/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Most concerning for the military is the hundreds of air-force reservists who have put their service on pause.预备役抗议领导人表示，其中包括数百名现役战斗机飞行员、无人机操作员、导航员和教员。 Unlike most reservists, air-force volunteers serve on a regular basis and are a pillar of the air force, itself a backbone of national security.</p><p> Many veteran reservists from air-force headquarters have suspended their service, said Naveh, although he couldn&#39;t provide specific numbers. They are called in to advise sometimes on regular operations and are crucial for the military during wartime.</p><p> “The reserve pilots are a cornerstone of the Air Force&#39;s operational ability to reach its goals, and their contribution to Israel&#39;s security is significant,” the Israeli military said when asked about the hundreds of air-force reservists refusing to serve. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-threatening-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“目前，空军完全有能力并做好了作战准备。长时间不报告可能会使[以色列国防军]和空军处于能力下降和战备状态下降的状态。”</p><p>当被问及有多少预备役军人暂停服役时，以色列军方拒绝发表评论。</p><p> Over time, the absences will impact the training schedule of Israel&#39;s air-force cadets, say instructors who have suspended their service.他们说，大多数教官都是拥有数十年经验的预备役军人，而且没有明确的替代者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1136" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828322?width=639&amp;height=1136" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">双桅船。 Gen. Offer Lapidot wears a T-shirt reading, “Dictatorship?决不。”</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Offer Lapidot</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>双桅船。 73 岁的空军学院前指挥官奥弗·拉皮多特将军表示，如果没有预备役军人的大力帮助，就没有足够的正规军教官为所有学员提供服务。</p><p> After spending his entire adult life in the air force, largely as a fighter pilot and commander, and until recently as an instructor, Lapidot sent his suspension-of-service letter to his commander a week and a half before Netanyahu&#39;s government passed the first judicial legislation. He said he had hoped to apply enough pressure to stop the bill from passing.</p><p>他说，他被迫权衡“国家的安全，与我们为之奋斗并准备献出生命的国家的存在”。</p><p> 46 岁的祖尔·阿隆 (Zur Allon) 是一名科技公司首席执行官，也是炮兵特种部队的常备役军人，他已暂停服役，不过自两周前开始就没有要求他去上班。他表示，如果国家发生紧急情况，他将到岗。但他担心长时间的停顿可能会影响军队的战斗准备。</p><p> “It is like a car: Leave it in the garage for a year and it won&#39;t work,” he said.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 10:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-throne-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-reservists-start-missing-duty-throne-military-unity-and-readiness-76df3ade<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>空军</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Armed Forces</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>空军</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China’s Latest Problem: People Don’t Want to Go There]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着地缘政治紧张局势加剧，前往世界第二大经济体的游客减少，东西方鸿沟扩大<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827041?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">近日，上海机场人烟稀少，旅行社组织的境外旅游来华的人数大幅减少。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：劳尔·阿里亚诺/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100887"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/wenxin-fan" itemprop="url" rel="author">范文欣</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Half a year after China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-xi-jinping-reversed-his-zero-covid-policy-in-china-11672853171?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">lifted Covid-19 restrictions</a> and reopened its borders, few international travelers are coming—another sign of decoupling between China and the West that could have negative repercussions for a long time.</p><p> Foreign travelers&#39; absence is particularly evident in major cities like Beijing and Shanghai, where the numbers of foreigners who visited in the first half of the year totaled less than a quarter of comparable figures in 2019, before the Covid pandemic.</p><p>在全国范围内，第一季度，只有 52,000 人次通过旅行社组织的旅行到达中国大陆，这是有全国数据的最新时期，而 2019 年第一季度有 370 万人次。与往年一样，近一半的游客来自自治岛屿台湾以及中国香港和澳门，而不是美国或欧洲等更远的地方。</p><p> “The number of visitors from Europe, America, Japan and Korea are all dropping, substantially,” said Xiao Qianhui, a director with the semiofficial China Tourism Association in a speech in May.</p><p> Fewer tourists and businesspeople from overseas means fewer opportunities for foreigners to see China with their own eyes and interact with locals, an important factor in reducing geopolitical tensions, experts say.</p><p> The dearth of visitors could also be contributing to less investment in China. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Foreign direct investment into the country fell</a> to $20 billion in the first quarter, compared with $100 billion in last year&#39;s first quarter, according to an analysis of government figures by Mark Witzke at Rhodium Group, a research firm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827059?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A mausoleum in Nanjing was swarmed with tourists in 2019, before the Covid pandemic hit.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Su Yang/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The drop in foreign investment and arrivals comes as China&#39;s economy stagnates, with a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-property-market-enters-troubling-new-phase-1fe3143d" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">depressed housing market</a> , youth <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">unemployment</a> at record highs and widening fears the country could be <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/while-everyone-else-fights-inflation-chinas-deflation-fears-deepen-4045cabf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">slipping into deflation.</a> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Chinese economy barely grew</a> in the second quarter from the first three months of the year.</p><p> A <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-allows-chinese-airlines-to-increase-flights-to-12-a-week-814327a8" target="_blank" class="icon none">shortage of available flights</a> to China is partly to blame for the low arrival numbers, with carriers not yet restoring the same level of service they offered pre-Covid. But Chinese and overseas tourism experts say foreign visitors are also staying away because of deteriorating relations between China and the West, which has made them more wary of visiting.</p><p> In June, the US government issued a travel advisory warning Americans to reconsider travel to mainland China due to what it called “the arbitrary enforcement of local laws,” including exit bans and the possibility of wrongful detentions.</p><p> Matt Kelly, a Boston-based business consultant, said he has fond memories of his trip 15 years ago cycling around Guilin, a picturesque hilly city in southern China. He visited China two more times, but said he had no interest in going back today.</p><p> “Would I go back to that China I knew? Yes!”他说。 But now, “China does seem to portray itself as very anti-Western, anti-American, specifically. It makes me very uneasy.”</p><p> Friendly Planet Travel, a Pennsylvania-based boutique operator, used to send as many as 1,500 tourists to China a year. Since Covid, it hasn&#39;t had a single request, said Peggy Goldman, its founder and president. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828850?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Matt Kelly in Guilin, China, in 2008.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Matt Kelly</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> When her team researched the destinations people are searching for online, “China is really at the bottom of that tracking,” she said. “There was a lot of animosity around the subject of China.”</p><p> The company has yet to put its China packages back online, although Goldman said she believes China will become popular again eventually.</p><p> Leisure travel from North America to China in the first half of 2023 was about 40% of the same period of 2019, according to Mondee Holdings, a travel technology company based in Austin. Mondee sold about half a million flights from North America to China in 2019 through travel agents and other intermediaries, roughly one-fifth of all air travel from North America to China that year.</p><p> Although business executives are still making inquiries about traveling to China, many now are focusing on risks, whereas in the past, they wanted to find out how to expedite a visa, said Dan Harris, a partner in Seattle at Harris Bricken, a law firm that advises on investments in China.</p><p> “Companies are very, very concerned about their people going to China. Why wouldn&#39;t they be?” he said, pointing to news of China&#39;s recent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/foreign-firms-in-china-squeezed-by-u-s-disclosure-demands-beijings-security-clampdown-658ef8f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">investigations into Western due-diligence and other firms</a> , which included government raids on global consultancies including Bain &amp; Co. “People are not going to China unless they have to.”</p><p> Harris, who used to go to China frequently for work in Beijing, with stops for beer and seafood in Qingdao, said he has told some executives their risks would be low. But he has himself stopped going, after becoming vocally critical of the Chinese government in recent years.</p><p> China&#39;s Ministry of Culture and Tourism didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> Chinese officials have held meetings with business associations from the US, Europe and Japan recently <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to reassure them</a> the country still welcomes foreign investment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="441" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827025?width=700&amp;height=441" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tourist visits to Zhangjiajie National Park have plummeted from 2019.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Wu Yongbing/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> China&#39;s ambassador to the US, Xie Feng, said at the Aspen Security Forum in July that tourists of both countries should visit each other. He suggested hosting a tourism forum and increasing the number of flights, and called on Washington to adjust its travel advisory.</p><p> The absence of foreign visitors won&#39;t hurt China the same way it would places like Thailand or Iceland, whose economies rely heavily on tourists. Chinese travelers <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-travelers-swarm-domestic-tourist-sites-a-positive-sign-for-economy-f45c4977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are now spending more on domestic tourism</a> than they did in 2019.</p><p> Still, there are many businesses in China that do count on visitors. The lack of them represents a lost opportunity for China to show itself in a more positive light to foreigners.</p><p> Central China&#39;s Zhangjiajie National Park, a region of striking rock formations where the “floating mountains” in the movie Avatar were filmed, recorded only 25,600 overseas visitors through mid-May, compared with 500,000 in the first five months of 2019.</p><p> Snow Yu, a Shanghai tourist guide, used to do a thriving business showing foreigners around, including acting as a guide for executives of the Golden State Warriors and Georgia Tech&#39;s Yellow Jackets basketball team in 2017. During the pandemic, when borders were largely closed, he took a temporary job tutoring English.</p><p> Yu has returned to his old job, leading mostly local tour groups. But they don&#39;t need his English skills and give fewer tips. As a result, he says his income is down by nearly half from before the pandemic. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5BD0F48A-0DA4-4CED-8A69-018103B38E36&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> President Biden said on Sunday he sees a potential thaw in relations between the US and China, in a news conference wrapping up the G-7 meeting in Japan. Photo: Susan Walsh/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“The world needs to be connected,” he said, adding that English-speaking visitors from neighboring countries are beginning to come back.</p><p> The drop in visitors from the West and parts of East Asia has been offset in part by an increase in the number of Russians arriving, though Chinese travel experts say they spend less.</p><p> In June, when Zhangjiajie, the national park, invited more than 80 international tourism agents to town, a majority came from Russia. Local officials promised to add more flights from China&#39;s northern neighbor or extend existing flights from other Chinese cities.</p><p> In his speech, Xiao, the tourism official, appealed for more support from the central government. He stressed that inbound tourism could help defuse geopolitical tensions “in ways similar to &#39;ping pong diplomacy,&#39;” referring to exchanges of table-tennis players in the 1970s that helped thaw relations between China and the US</p><p> He cited a recent China visit by Elon Musk&#39;s mother, who posted positive messages about her experience on Instagram.</p><p> Another group that is steering clear of China is expatriates, who in previous years acted as bridges between Chinese society and their respective home countries. Many invited family and friends to visit.</p><p> Investment consultant Alexander Sirakov, 37, moved back to his home country Bulgaria from Shanghai last August. He said that most people in his wider circle of expatriate friends also departed, including eight out of the 10 expat families living in his compound.</p><p> “People now perceive China as very distant and somewhat alienated,” he said. “It was exactly the opposite four years ago, when China was really open and vibrant, a must-go place.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Liyan Qi contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Wenxin Fan at <a href="mailto:wenxin.fan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wenxin.fan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-latest-problem-people-dont-want-to-go-there-7d17a83a<author><![CDATA[Wenxin Fan]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Respiratory Tract Diseases</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Novel Coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>respiratory tract diseases</category><category>国际关系</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>lifestyle</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>政治</category><category>novel coronaviruses</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>旅行</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Real Reason You’re Having a Hard Time Getting Things Done at the Office]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在家工作改变了我们的大脑。我们需要更多的办公时间来解决这些问题。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828457/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>照片插图：Sam Kelly/《华尔街日报》，iStock (11)<span>照片插图：Sam Kelly/《华尔街日报》，iStock (11)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105097"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ray-a-smith" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷·A·史密斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 3 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>如果你还没有恢复办公室的最佳状态，可能会有一个科学的解释。混合工作安排会扰乱我们的大脑。</p><p>沮丧的老板们在审视<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-return-to-office-rate-rises-above-50-for-first-time-since-pandemic-began-11675285071?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">半空的办公室环境</a>后表示，2020 年之前在办公室全职工作的人不能像以前那样出现，这是没有道理的。但神经学家和行为科学家表示，对彼此有效合作的集体失忆症对他们来说是完全合理的。</p><p>一些员工已经失去了在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-open-office-is-out-seated-privacy-is-in-as-cubicles-make-a-comeback-11663189508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开放式办公室环境</a>中完成工作所需的肌肉记忆，就像松弛的二头肌一样，这种肌肉必须通过锻炼才能增强，教授兼神经病学系主任托马斯·卡迈克尔 (S. Thomas Carmichael) 说。加州大学洛杉矶分校大卫格芬医学院。</p><p>卡迈克尔说，经过多年的远程工作，我们大脑的选择性注意力技能和排除干扰的能力被削弱。那些喜欢在家工作的人可能不喜欢他的补救措施之一：让自己更频繁地在办公室工作。</p><p> “大脑真的很擅长理解突发事件，所以如果我们只是说‘我在家的时候就完成这件事’，我们也学不会它，”他说。</p><h3>淹没在“假设”的海洋中</h3><p>组织心理学家凯瑟琳·斯沃迪 (Cathleen Swody) 表示，在了解在家工作的有效性之后，人们心里产生了一种隐隐约约的不快感。许多员工在社交办公空间中失去了不受干扰的自主权。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="479" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828332?width=639&amp;height=479" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">玛丽亚·巴比诺娃 (Maryia Babinova) 表示，即使是很小的办公室时间浪费也已成为一大烦恼。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：玛丽亚·巴比诺娃</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>早在 2021 年，纽约市的高级软件工程师玛丽亚·巴比诺娃 (Maryia Babinova) 曾尝试每周去办公室几天，但发现几乎不可能提高工作效率。</p><p> “我每天的前 30 到 45 分钟都用来和每个人打招呼，”她说。</p><p>巴比诺娃表示，即使是很小的办公室时间浪费也已成为一大烦恼。例如，当排队时，去办公室的咖啡机可能需要长达 15 分钟的时间。她说，在家里，咖啡因触手可及，让她能够专注于工作。</p><p>现在，只有当她的团队成员从另一个城市来访时，巴比诺娃才会亲自出现。在办公室，她处理的任务不需要太多的精神负担，因此她可以完成它们。</p><p>伦敦经济学院助理教授劳拉·M·乔治 (Laura M. Giurge) 教授工作时间科学课程，她表示，不断将 2023 年的办公室现实与其他远程工作设置进行比较可能会加剧员工的重新调整困境。</p><p>当人们开始思考如果环境不同的话生活会是什么样子时，他们很快就会陷入“假设”的海洋，这是一种被称为反事实思维的心理学概念。</p><p> “现在，当我们去办公室时，我们会看到家庭办公室的反事实情况，”朱尔格说。 “我们知道事情会好得多……我们可以完成更多的工作。”</p><p>我们很难忘记<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-workers-really-spend-their-days-d06c8f5f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中午带着狗去散步</a>是多么美好，或者下午 4 点退出并开始吃晚饭并稍后重新登录是多么有帮助。心理学家表示，思考如何更好地利用时间会占用宝贵的脑力，分散我们对手头实际工作的注意力。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>令人不安的安静</h3><p>习惯与背景噪音一起工作需要时间。</p><p>现在，许多工作场所变得更加安静，因为它们不再那么拥挤，这意味着，在一段死寂的时期，可能会被突然的噪音打断，这些噪音感觉被放大了，一整天都让人们一次又一次感到不安。即使是在一天在家孤独工作和第二天在嘈杂的办公室之间切换也会产生类似的效果。</p><p>康奈尔大学组织行为学教授凡妮莎·博恩斯 (Vanessa Bohns) 表示：“我们必须重新习惯所有这些干扰，才能做好工作。”她指出，研究表明，需要 20 分钟才能适应背景噪音，但在恢复噪音之前保持五分钟的安静会迫使大脑重新开始处理过程。</p><p>现在，许多员工和一些老板将办公室视为协作的场所，但并不是埋头进行个人工作的唯一场所。</p><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>去年发布的一项大规模调查中，84% 的员工表示，与同事交流是他们面对面工作的主要动机。超过 70% 的人表示，如果他们知道直接团队成员或工作朋友会在那里，他们会更频繁地去办公室。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否发现在办公室完成工作比大流行之前更困难？为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “数据显示，我们不能只将办公室视为完成集中工作的地方，”微软未来工作部总经理科莱特·斯塔尔鲍默 (Colette Stallbaumer) 表示。</p><p> Lynn Dang 是达拉斯地区的一名软件开发人员，她利用三天的强制办公时间进行面对面的会议和不需要高度集中注意力的工作。</p><p>去年，当她回到办公室时，她发现自己无法像在家工作时那样专心阅读代码。大声的团队讨论以及在小隔间里无意中听到那些正在打电话或拨入视频会议的人的片面谈话，对她的感官造成了持续的攻击。</p><p> “这就像我必须在我的待办事项清单上找到一些能让我高效工作的事情，”她说。 “否则我将不得不继续加班或周末工作才能完成工作。”</p><p>写信给 Ray A. Smith： <a href="mailto:Ray.Smith@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Ray.Smith@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 03 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-real-reason-youre-having-a-hard-time-getting-things-done-at-the-office-5dc138f1<author><![CDATA[Ray A. Smith]]></author><category> wsjlifework</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>远程办公</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> S·托马斯·卡迈克尔</category><category>凯瑟琳·斯沃迪</category><category>劳拉·M·乔治</category><category>凡妮莎·博恩斯</category><category>科莱特·斯托鲍默</category><category>工作与生活的平衡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>活的</category><category>lifestyle</category><category>远程办公</category></item></channel></rss>